If the Operator transports revenue cargo, the Operator shall have a manager for cargo operation hat:

	(i) Has the authority and responsibility for the management and supervision of functions an ctivities within the scope of cargo operations;

	(ii) Is responsible for the management of safety and security risks to cargo operations.

If the Operator transports revenue cargo, the Operator shall ensure the management system define he safety accountability, authorities and responsibilities of management and non-managemen ersonnel that perform functions relevant to the safety and/or security of cargo operations. Th anagement system shall also specify:

	(i) The levels of management with the authority to make decisions regarding risk tolerabilit ith respect to the safety and/or security of cargo operations;

	(ii) Responsibilities for ensuring cargo operations are conducted in accordance with applicabl egulations and standards of the Operator;

	(iii) Lines of accountability throughout cargo operations, including direct accountability for safet nd/or security on the part of cargo operations senior management.

If the Operator transports cargo, the Operator shall have a system that enables effectiv ommunication of relevant safety and operational information throughout the cargo operation anagement system and in all areas where cargo operations are conducted. Such system shal nsure:

	(i) Personnel maintain an awareness of the SMS;

	(ii) Safety-critical information is conveyed;

	(iii) If applicable, external service providers are provided with information relevant to operation onducted

If the Operator transports revenue cargo, the Operator shall have a system for the management an ontrol of documentation and/or data used directly in the conduct or support of cargo operations.
Such system shall ensure documentation:

	(i) Meets all required elements specified in Table 1.1 ;

	(ii) Contains legible and accurate information;

	(iii) Is presented in a format appropriate for use in operations.

If the Operator transports cargo, the Operator shall have a system for the management and control o perational records to ensure the content and retention of such records is in accordance wit equirements of the Authority, as applicable, and to ensure operational records are subjected t tandardized processes for:

	(i) Identification;

	(ii) Legibility;

	(iii) Maintenance;

	(iv) Retrieval;

	(v) Protection, integrity and security;

	(vi) Disposal, deletion (electronic records) and archiving.

If the Operator transports cargo, the Operator shall have a quality assurance program that provide or the auditing and evaluation of the management system and operational functions within the scop f cargo operations at planned intervals to ensure the Operator is:

	(i) Complying with applicable regulations and standards;

	(ii) Satisfying stated operational needs;

	(iii) Identifying areas requiring improvement;

	(iv) Identifying hazards to operations;

	(v) Assessing the effectiveness of safety risk controls.

If the Operator transports cargo, the Operator shall have a process for addressing findings resultin rom audits conducted under the quality assurance program, which ensures:

	(i) Identification of root cause(s);

	(ii) Development of corrective action, as appropriate to address findings;

	(iii) Implementation of corrective action in appropriate areas of cargo operations;

	(iv) Evaluation of corrective action to determine effectiveness.

If the Operator transports cargo, the Operator shall have an audit planning process and sufficien esources to ensure audits of cargo operations are:

	(i) Scheduled at intervals to meet regulatory and management system requirements;

	(ii) Conducted within the scheduled interval.

If the Operator has external service providers conduct outsourced cargo operations functions, th perator should ensure a service provider selection process is in place that ensures:

	(i) Safety-relevant selection criteria are established;

	(ii) Service providers are evaluated against these criteria prior to selection.

If the Operator transports cargo, the Operator shall have a safety risk assessment and mitigatio rogram implemented in the cargo operations organization that specifies processes to ensure:

	(i) Hazards are analyzed to determine the corresponding safety risks to aircraft operations;

	(ii) Safety risks are assessed to determine the requirement for risk mitigation action(s);

	(iii) When required, risk mitigation actions are developed and implemented in cargo operations.

If the Operator transports cargo, the Operator shall have an operational safety reporting system i he cargo operations organization that:

	(i) Encourages and facilitates cargo operations personnel to submit reports that identify safet azards, expose safety deficiencies and raise safety concerns;

	(ii) Includes analysis and cargo operations management action to address operationa eficiencies, hazards, incidents and concerns identified through the reporting system.

If the Operator transports cargo, the Operator shall have a process to ensure personnel that perfor perational duties in functions within the scope of cargo operations for the Operator, to includ ersonnel of external service providers, complete:

	(i) Initial training prior to being assigned to perform such operational duties;

	(ii) Recurrent training on a frequency in accordance with requirements of the regulator uthority but not less than once during every 36-month period, except for recurrent trainin n dangerous goods as specified in CGO 2.2.1 ,CGO 2.2.2 orCGO 2.2.3 .

If the Operator transports cargo, the Operator shall have a process to ensure the training program ompleted by cargo operations personnel in accordance with CGO 2.1.1 provide the knowledg ecessary to perform duties, execute procedures and operate the equipment associated with specifi argo functions and responsibilities. Such programs shall include:

	(i) Familiarization training on applicable regulations;

	(ii) In-depth training on requirements, including policies, procedures and operating practices;

	(iii) Training in human factors principles;

	(iv) Safety training on associated operational hazards.

If the Operator transports cargo, the Operator shall have a process to ensure training for personne hat perform operational duties within the scope of cargo operations for the Operator:

	(i) Includes testing or evaluation by written, oral or practical means, as applicable;

	(ii) Requires a demonstration of adequate knowledge, competency and proficiency to perfor uties, execute procedures and/or operate equipment.

If the Operator transports cargo, the Operator shall have a process to ensure such shipment ccepted for transport:

	(i) If revenue cargo, are in compliance with standards in the OM as specified in CGO 1.6.1 ;

	(ii) If interline cargo, are in compliance with IATA interline cargo requirements;

	(iii) If non-revenue cargo, are in compliance with the OM or equivalent document as specified i GO 1.6.1 .

If the Operator transports dangerous goods as cargo, the Operator shall have a Dangerous Good cceptance Checklist that:

	(i) Reflects applicable requirements contained in the current DGR;

	(ii) Once completed, contains information that identifies the person(s) that performed th cceptance check.

If the Operator transports dangerous goods as cargo, the Operator shall have procedures to ensur he use of a Dangerous Goods Acceptance Checklist as specified in CGO 3.2.1 to verify:

	(i) Package(s), overpack(s) or freight containers, as applicable, are correctly marked an abeled;

	(ii) The Shipper's Declaration for Dangerous Goods, if required, or other documentatio omplies with the requirements of the current edition of the DGR.

If the Operator transports dangerous goods as cargo, the Operator shall have procedures to ensur ny package, overpack, freight container, or ULD containing dangerous goods is inspected and is no ccepted, unless:

	(i) Properly marked and labeled;

	(ii) There is no leakage;

	(iii) Its integrity has not been compromised.

If the Operator transports dangerous goods as cargo on or in ULDs, the Operator shall hav rocedures to ensure ULDs containing dangerous goods, which require a hazard label, have  angerous goods tag that:

	(i) Contains information that is visible and legible and, if placed in a protective tag holder, suc nformation remains visible and legible;

	(ii) Is marked with the class and/or division number(s) of such dangerous goods;

	(iii) If a ULD contains packages bearing a  Cargo Aircraft Only  label, indicates the ULD ca nly be loaded onto a cargo aircraft.

If the Operator transports dangerous goods as cargo, the Operator shall have procedures to ensur ny dangerous goods shipment that appears to be damaged or leaking:

	(i) Is not to be loaded on or into a ULD or delivered to an aircraft;

	(ii) Is safely removed from the ULD (or other transport device) by the Provider or other relevan uthority, and safe disposal arranged;

	(iii) In the case of leakage, an evaluation is conducted to ensure the remainder of the shipmen s in proper condition for transport by air and that no other package, cargo, ULD, othe ransport device has been contaminated or damaged.

If the Operator transports dangerous goods as cargo, the Operator shall have procedures tha nsure information on dangerous goods to be loaded on a flight is communicated to the appropriat erson(s) responsible for load control. Information to be communicated shall include the following:

	(i) If applicable, Air Waybill number; 

	(ii) Proper shipping name and UN/ID number;

	(iii) Class or division, and subsidiary hazards corresponding to label(s) applied, and for Class 1,
compatibility group;

	(iv) If applicable, packing group;

	(v) For non-radioactive material, number of packages, exact loading location and, a pplicable, net quantity or gross weight of each package, except:

		(a) For UN 1845, carbon dioxide, solid (dry ice): At the option of the Operator, only th N number, proper shipping name, classification, total quantity in each aircraft hol nd offload airport are required;

		(b) For UN 3480, (Lithium ion batteries) and UN 3090 (lithium metal batteries): At th ption of the Operator, only the UN number, proper shipping name, class, tota uantity at each loading location, and whether the package must be carried on  argo-only aircraft are required. UN 3480 (Lithium ion batteries) and UN 3090
(lithium metal batteries) carried under a State exemption shall meet all requirement pecified in iv) and v).

	(vi) For radioactive material, number and category of packages, overpacks or freight containers,
exact loading locations and, as applicable, transport index and dimensions for eac ackage;

	(vii) Any restriction for transport on cargo aircraft only;

	(viii) Offload airport;

	(ix) If applicable, dangerous goods transported under a state exemption.

If the Operator transports cargo, the Operator shall have a process to ensure reports are provided t he appropriate authorities of the State of the Operator and the state of occurrence, in accordanc ith the reporting requirements of the appropriate authorities, for:

	(i) Dangerous goods accidents or dangerous goods incidents;

	(ii) Undeclared or mis-declared dangerous goods discovered in cargo or mail.

If the Operator transports live animals as cargo, the Operator should have procedures that ensure:

	(i) The acceptance and handling of live animals is in accordance with requirements of the Liv nimal Regulations (LAR);

	(ii) The IATA Live Animals Acceptance Check List, or equivalent, is used for the acceptance o ive animal shipments.

If the Operator transports cargo, the Operator shall ensure procedures are in place for the screenin f persons and the security control of vehicles in accordance with requirements of the applicable civi viation security program. Such procedures shall apply to persons and vehicles:

	(i) Under its control that have unescorted access to security restricted areas (in which there i argo);

	(ii) Not under its control but have unescorted access to such areas as authorized by th perator.

If the Operator transports cargo, the Operator shall have processes for the acceptance of cargo a ollows:

	(i) For cargo that can be identified as having the application of screening or other securit ontrols confirmed or accounted for by a regulated agent or an entity approved by th elevant authority (known cargo), a process to ensure such cargo is:

		(a) Delivered by a regulated agent, a nominated representative of an entity approve y the relevant authority, or a known representative of the operator;

		(b) Free from any signs of tampering;

		(c) Accompanied by all required information (paper or electronic) corresponding to th argo being delivered, including documentation that details the security status
(e.g. consignment security declaration); 

		(d) Protected from unauthorized interference throughout the chain of custody since th oint that cargo gained its secured status;

		(e) Subjected to additional security controls as required by risk assessment.

	(ii) For cargo that cannot be identified as having the application of screening or other securit ontrols confirmed or accounted for by a regulated agent or an entity approved by th elevant authority (unknown cargo), a process to ensure such cargo is subjected t creening or other security controls as accepted by the applicable state.
